### Tasks in C#

Task represents an asynchronous operation. It is the foundation of the Task Parallel Library (TPL).

### Creating Tasks

```csharp
// Using Task.Run (common)
Task task = Task.Run(() => DoWork());
Task<int> taskWithResult = Task.Run(() => ComputeResult());

// Using Task.Factory
Task task = Task.Factory.StartNew(() => DoWork());

// Using new Task (must call Start)
Task task = new Task(() => DoWork());
task.Start();

// Task from result
Task<int> completed = Task.FromResult(42);
```

### Waiting for Tasks

```csharp
Task task = Task.Run(() => DoWork());

task.Wait();            // Block until complete (avoid in async code)
bool done = task.Wait(1000);  // Wait with timeout

task.WaitAll(task1, task2);   // Wait for all
task.WaitAny(task1, task2);   // Wait for any
```

### Task Status

```csharp
Console.WriteLine(task.Status);
// Created, WaitingForActivation, Running,
// RanToCompletion, Faulted, Canceled
```

### Continuation

```csharp
Task<int> task = Task.Run(() => 42);

// Then (sequential)
Task continuation = task.ContinueWith(t =>
{
    Console.WriteLine(t.Result * 2);
});

// Only on success
task.ContinueWith(t => ProcessResult(t.Result),
    TaskContinuationOptions.OnlyOnRanToCompletion);

// Only on fault
Task faultHandler = task.ContinueWith(t =>
{
    Console.WriteLine(t.Exception);
}, TaskContinuationOptions.OnlyOnFaulted);
```

### Cancellation

```csharp
CancellationTokenSource cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
CancellationToken token = cts.Token;

Task task = Task.Run(() =>
{
    for (int i = 0; i < 1000; i++)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        // Do work...
    }
}, token);

// Cancel after 1 second
cts.CancelAfter(1000);
```

### Error Handling

```csharp
try
{
    await Task.Run(() => { throw new InvalidOperationException(); });
}
catch (AggregateException ae)
{
    foreach (var ex in ae.InnerExceptions)
        Console.WriteLine(ex.Message);
}
catch (InvalidOperationException ex)  // When using await
{
    Console.WriteLine(ex.Message);
}
```

### Task.Run vs Task.Factory.StartNew

| Aspect | Task.Run | Task.Factory.StartNew |
|--------|----------|----------------------|
| Simplicity | Simple | More options |
| Default scheduler | TaskScheduler.Default | Can specify |
| For CPU-bound work | Preferred | Advanced scenarios |

> **Key Point:** Use `Task.Run` for CPU-bound work. Use `await` instead of `.Wait()` or `.Result` to avoid deadlocks. Tasks support cancellation, continuation, and error handling. `Task.WhenAll` and `Task.WhenAny` combine multiple tasks.

### Task Combinators

```csharp
Task all = Task.WhenAll(task1, task2);  // Wait for all
var any = Task.WhenAny(task1, task2);   // First to complete
```

### Parallel.For/ForEach

```csharp
Parallel.For(0, 100, i => Process(i));
Parallel.ForEach(items, item => Process(item));
```

### Task.Delay vs Thread.Sleep

```csharp
await Task.Delay(1000);     // Non-blocking (async)
Thread.Sleep(1000);         // Blocking (sync)
```

codeExample:
using System;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

class Program
{
    static async Task Main()
    {
        // Run multiple tasks in parallel
        Task<int> task1 = Task.Run(() => Compute(1));
        Task<int> task2 = Task.Run(() => Compute(2));
        Task<int> task3 = Task.Run(() => Compute(3));

        int[] results = await Task.WhenAll(task1, task2, task3);
        Console.WriteLine($"Results: {string.Join(", ", results)}");
        Console.WriteLine($"Total: {await SumAsync(results)}");
    }

    static int Compute(int id)
    {
        Task.Delay(500).Wait();  // Simulate work
        return id * 10;
    }

    static async Task<int> SumAsync(int[] numbers)
    {
        await Task.Delay(100);
        int sum = 0;
        foreach (var n in numbers) sum += n;
        return sum;
    }
}
